{{#system~}}
Analyze the provided  URL in the <ProvidedURL> block.
Validate and transform it according to <ExplicitConstraints> and <OutputFormat> rules.

---

<ExplicitConstraints alt="explicit constraints">
If <ProvidedURL> block contains something which does not look like a valid URL:
  - Set `input_url_is_valid` as `false`
  - Set `output_refined_transformed_url` as "null"
Examples for invalid URL:
  - `https://example` (missing top-level domain part)
  - `.com` (missing second-level domain part)
Examples for valid URL:
  - `https://example.com` (without `www.`)
  - `https://www.example.com` (with `www.`)
  - `www.example.com` (without `https://`)
  - `example.com` (without `https://www.` or similar)
  - `http://www.example.com` (HTTP protocol)
  - `https://www.example.com/hello_world?view=XXXXXXXXXXX&item=Y` (with functional query parameters)
</ExplicitConstraints>

---

<OutputFormat alt="rules regarding output format">
1. The output must be a valid JSON object generated according to provided schema.
2. `output_refined_transformed_url`:
  - Must be a valid URL without any additional redundant non-functional query parameters or "null"
  - Leave HTTP protocol as is if specified. If not, set it to `https://`
</OutputFormat>

